04296nam a22005175i 9780773588127DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735881277 a10.1515/97807735881272doi  a(DE-B1597)656476  a(OCoLC)842266015  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aDA426b.W66 2013eb 7aHIS0150002bisacsh04a941.06/40922231 aWoodford, Benjamin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPerceptions of a Monarchy without a King :bReactions to Oliver Cromwell's Power /cBenjamin Woodford. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOliver Cromwell’s Kingship Speeches and the Arguments of the Kingship Committee -- tThe Absence of Kingship in Printed Propaganda -- tMercurius Politicus: A Newsbook’s Account of the Kingship Crisis -- tCromwellian Writers: Marchamont Nedham, John Milton, and Michael Hawke -- tCromwellian Poets: Edmund Waller, Andrew Marvell, George Wither, and John Lineall -- tCromwellian Monarchists and Stuart Loyalists: A Split in the Royalist Movement -- tReligious Reactions to Cromwellian Power -- tJames Harrington’s Oceana and Its Relation to the Protectorate -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOliver Cromwell had not a drop of royal blood in him. Yet in 1657, prompted by the political chaos that followed the execution of Charles I and inspired by a belief that a return to monarchy was the only way to stabilize the nation, parliament offered Cromwell the crown of Britain. In Perceptions of a Monarchy without a King, Benjamin Woodford explores how factions both inside and outside of government reacted to this unprecedented event. Moving away from a biographical focus on Cromwell, Woodford looks to the print culture of the period to examine kingship and the Cromwellian regime as a complex phenomenon that elicited diverse reactions - from broadly in favour to dead-set against. Woodford analyzes Cromwell's speeches along with propaganda, newspapers, poetry, republican writings, and the works of religious sects. The fact that many of these writings were produced by men and women who were not members of the government demonstrates that both politicians and the general public were interested in the topics of Cromwell and kingship. Cromwell's military and political power rendered him a candidate for kingship, but even with his record of achievement, the offer of the crown to a non-nobleman was controversial. Perceptions of a Monarchy without a King reveals the entire nation's responses to the kingship debates while simultaneously illustrating the persistence of the monarchy in the 1650s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMonarchyzGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358812740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773588127423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773588127/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles